{{Infobox language |name = Baduy language |nativename = Basa Baduy / Badui |region = [[Java]], [[Indonesia]] |speakers = 11,620 |date = 2010 census |ref = <ref name="TBACAPOEP">{{cite web|url=http://biodiversitas.mipa.uns.ac.id/D/D1702/D170244.pdf |title=Ethnoastronomy-The Baduy agricultural calendar and prediction of environmental perturbations |author=Johan Iskandar & Budiawati S. Iskandar |publisher=BIODIVERSITAS Volume 17, Number 2 |page=696 |issn=1412-033X |date=October 2016 |accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref> |familycolor = Austronesian |fam2 = [[Nuclear Malayo-Polynesian languages|Nuclear Malayo-Polynesian]] |fam3 = [[Malayo-Sumbawan languages|Malayo-Sumbawan]] |fam4 = [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] |script = ''none'' |iso3 = bac |isoexception = dialect |glotto = badu1237 |glottorefname = Baduy }}
'''Baduy''' or '''Badui''' language is spoken by [[Baduy people]].<ref>{{cite web|url=https://joshuaproject.net/languages/bac |title=Language: Badui |publisher=[[Joshua Project]] |accessdate=2017-07-17}}</ref> Native speakers of the language are spread in Mount Kendeng, [[Rangkasbitung]] district of [[Lebak Regency]], [[Pandeglang Regency]] and [[Sukabumi]], [[West Java]], [[Indonesia]]. It is estimated that there are 11,620 speakers as of 2010.<ref name="TBACAPOEP"/>
The Baduy language is closely related to [[Sundanese language|Sundanese]] and sometimes considered a dialect of the latter.
